An intermediate level of abstraction for computational systems chemistry.

Andersen JL(1)(2), Flamm C(3)(4), Merkle D(5), Stadler PF(6)(7)(8)(9)(10).

Author information:
(1)Earth-Life Science Institute, Tokyo Institute of Technology, Tokyo 152-8550, 
Japan.
(2)Department of Mathematics and Computer Science, University of Southern 
Denmark, Odense 5230, Denmark.
(3)Institute for Theoretical Chemistry, University of Vienna, Wien 1090, 
Austria.
(4)Research Network Chemistry Meets Microbiology, University of Vienna, Wien 
1090, Austria.
(5)Department of Mathematics and Computer Science, University of Southern 
Denmark, Odense 5230, Denmark daniel@imada.sdu.dk.
(6)Bioinformatics Group, Department of Computer Science, and Interdisciplinary 
Center for Bioinformatics, University of Leipzig, Leipzig D-04107, Germany.
(7)Max Planck Institute for Mathematics in the Sciences, Leipzig D-04103, 
Germany.
(8)Fraunhofer Institute for Cell Therapy and Immunology, Leipzig D-04103, 
Germany.
(9)Center for Non-coding RNA in Technology and Health, University of Copenhagen, 
Frederiksberg C 1870, Denmark.
(10)Santa Fe Institute, 1399 Hyde Park Road, Santa Fe, NM 87501, USA.

Computational techniques are required for narrowing down the vast space of 
possibilities to plausible prebiotic scenarios, because precise information on 
the molecular composition, the dominant reaction chemistry and the conditions 
for that era are scarce. The exploration of large chemical reaction networks is 
a central aspect in this endeavour. While quantum chemical methods can 
accurately predict the structures and reactivities of small molecules, they are 
not efficient enough to cope with large-scale reaction systems. The 
formalization of chemical reactions as graph grammars provides a generative 
system, well grounded in category theory, at the right level of abstraction for 
the analysis of large and complex reaction networks. An extension of the basic 
formalism into the realm of integer hyperflows allows for the identification of 
complex reaction patterns, such as autocatalysis, in large reaction networks 
using optimization techniques.This article is part of the themed issue 
'Reconceptualizing the origins of life'.

